[1]
Date: Fri 26 Aug 2005
From: Mary Marshall <tropical.forestry@btinternet.com>
Source: Reuters Alertnet, 26 Aug 2005 [edited]
<http://www.alertnet.org/thenews/newsdesk/L26180726.htm>

Another foot and mouth outbreak reported in Russia
-----------------------------------------------
Russian health officials were checking on Friday [26 Aug 2005] on reports
of an outbreak of foot and mouth disease (FMD) in another region in the
country's far east.
Last week [3rd week August 2005], FMD was found in 2 settlements in
Russia's Khabarovsk region, where farmers were due to slaughter dozens of
cows to stop the disease from spreading.
Itar-Tass news agency reported that FMD may have spread to the neighboring
Primorsk region on the Pacific coast, where 15 cows in the village of
Krasny Kut had shown symptoms similar to those of foot and mouth disease.
The Emergencies Ministry's office in the region was unavailable for comment.
Foot and mouth disease does not harm humans, but it is highly contagious
among cattle, affecting reproduction and reducing meat output.
Russia is already busy trying to contain an outbreak of the deadly bird flu
disease, which has swept 6 Siberian regions since mid-July 2005.
